THE ANIL, οη INDIGO.

That mass of blue colour which the Spaniards call afiil, or anir, and other Europeans, indigo, is made of a plant, with a long slender root, branching out into a number of shoots3 on which account its long stalks partly creep on the ground, and partly stand upright. They are red on one side, and are loaden with small boughs, and round leaves, 'about the size of one's little finger nail, of a dark green, on one side, and a silvery white on the other. The little blossoms of this plant are of a palish red, with flowers like a husk of corn, or as others explain it, like an open helmet: and are suc- ceeded by podS‚ hanging from the stalk, full of an olive-coloured seed, very like rape seed.
